===Etymology 2===
From {{proto|Germanic|sīnaz|lang=nl}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|seino-|lang=nl}}, originally a reflexive form. Cognate with German ''[[sein]]'', Swedish ''[[sin]]''. Ultimately a form of Proto-Indo-European [[Appendix:Proto-Indo-European_*swé|*swe]], related to Russian [[себя]] (sebja), Latin [[suus]], Greek [[ἑός]] (heos), Sanskrit (sva) etc.

